  "prompt": "How do you determine the pH of hydrofluoric acid?",
  "response": "To determine the pH of hydrofluoric acid (HF), you can follow these steps:\n\n1. Measure the concentration of HF solution\n\n2. Look up the acid dissociation constant (Ka) for HF\n- Ka for HF is approximately 3.5 x 10^-4 at room temperature\n\n3. Use the acid dissociation equation:\nHF \u21cc H+ + F-\n\n4. Calculate pH using the Ka expression:\nKa = [H+][F-] / [HF]\n\n5. Use pH calculation methods:\n- For dilute solutions: pH = -log[H+]\n- For weak acids: pH = 1/2 (pKa - log[HF])\n\n6. Experimental methods:\n- Use a pH meter\n- Perform a titration\n- Use pH indicator strips\n\n7. Consider factors affecting pH:\n- Concentration of HF\n- Temperature\n- Presence of other ions\n\nThe specific calculation will depend on the concentration of the HF solution and the precise experimental conditions.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these steps?",
